    <h1>HTML Forms Demo Page</h1>
    <hr>
    <p>Let's get into forms by... you guessed it... creating forms ;)</p>
    <p>
        <u>The Form Element:</u> Is a shell or contatiner that doesn't have any visual imact. We fill the form with a
        collection of inputs, checkboxes, buttons, ect.
    </p>
    <p>
        <u>The Input Element:</u> is used to create a variety of different form controls. There are 20+ possible types
        of inputes, ranging from date pickers to checkboxes. The <i>type</i> attribute is where the magic happens.
        Changing <i>type</i> dramatically alters the inputs's behaviour and appearance.
        <br>
        <br>
        Below you will see multiple form <u>labels</u> and <u>inputs</u>.
    </p>
    <hr>
    <form action="/trends">
        <p>
            <label for="username">Enter Username here:</label>
            <input type="text" placeholder="Username" id="username">
        </p>
        <p>
            <label for="password">Enter Password here:</label>
            <input type="password" placeholder="Password" id="password">
        </p>

        <p>
            <label for="color">Enter Color here:</label>
            <input type="color" name="" id="color">
        </p>

        <p>
            <label for="month">Choose a Month:</label>
            <input type="month" placeholder="Enter a Month" id="month">
        </p>
        <p>
            <label for="number">Enter a Number:</label>
            <input type="number" placeholder=" Enter a Number" id="number">
        </p>
        <p>
            <label for="email">Enter your Email:</label>
            <input type="email" placeholder="Enter an Email" id="email">
        </p>
    </form>
    <hr>
    <h3>HTML Buttons</h3>
    <hr>
    <p>
        <button>Submit</button>
        You need to specify "type" to direct the button.
    </p>
    <hr>
    <p>Cool Reddit/Google search hack</p>
    <p>Reddit Search Hack</p>
    <form action="https://www.reddit.com/search" target="_blank">

        <input type="text" name="q">
        <button>Search Reddit</button>
    </form>
    <p>Google Search Hack</p>
    <form action="https://www.google.com/search" target="_blank">

        <input type="text" name="q">
        <button>Search Google</button>
    </form>
    <hr>
    <h3>Additional Input Elements.</h3>
    <hr>
    <p>Checkbox Input</p>

    <input type="checkbox" name="Checkbox" id="checkbox" checked>
    <label for="checkbox">Click Here</label>
    <hr>
    <p>Radio Input</p>
    <p>
        <label for="Wordpress">Wordpress</label>
        <input type="radio" name="crm" id="Wordpress">
    </p>
    <p>
        <label for="Shopify">Shopify</label>
        <input type="radio" name="crm" id="Shopify">
    </p>
    <label for="Wix">Wix</label>
    <input type="radio" name="crm" id="Wix">
    <hr>
    <p>The Select Element</p>
    <p>The Select Element is the parent of the Option Element, they work together to build out a selection table.</p>
    <label for="crm">CRM used --> </label>
    <select name="crm" id="crm">

        <option value="Wordpress">Wordpress</option>
        <option value="Shopify">Shopify</option>
        <option value="Wix">Wix</option>
    </select>
    <hr>

    <h3>Other useful Inputs to know</h3>
    <hr>
    <p>The Range input</p>
    <label for="wordpress">Worpress Skills</label>
    <input type="range" name="wp" id="wordpress" min="1" max="100">
    <br>
    <label for="shopify">Shopify Skills</label>
    <input type="range" name="sh" id="shopify">
    <br>
    <label for="wix">Wix Skills</label>
    <input type="range" name="wix" id="wix">
    <br>
    <h3>Textarea</h3>
    <p>

        <Textarea id="words" rows="10" cols="80" placeholder="Your wise words here"></Textarea>

    </p>
    <hr>
    <h3>HTML Form Validations</h3>
    <hr>
    <p>
        Form validators are used when a form option is required. A great example of this is when you have to use a
        minimum amount of characters in a password.
    </p>
    <p>One of the most common Validators is "required" which you will need to add to the input element.</p>



